{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586626"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15081"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15081"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.05,0,0.19,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64428"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7769"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8129"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21226"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64428"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBladder cancer is the ninth most common cancer worldwide and responsible for about 3% of all cancers in Australia. It is diagnosed in about 3000 individuals in this country every year. The type of bladder cancer varies, depending on histological subtypes arising from different cell types within the bladder wall.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common type of bladder cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenocarcinoma","Leiomyosarcoma","Small cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Transitional cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransitional cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (also called urothelial carcinoma) accounts for approximately 90-95% of all bladder cancers in developed countries. It arises from the transitional epithelium that lines the bladder.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E represents less than 2% of bladder cancers and typically develops from areas of metaplasia. \u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for about 5% of cases in developed countries but is more common in regions where schistosomiasis is endemic.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeiomyosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare mesenchymal tumour arising from smooth muscle cells. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmall cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the bladder is an aggressive neuroendocrine tumour that comprises less than 1% of all bladder cancers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transitional cell carcinoma accounts for over 90% of all bladder cancers.","Risk factors for bladder cancer include smoking, occupational chemical exposure, and chronic inflammation."],"references":["Comp\u00e9rat E, Amin MB, Cathomas R, Choudhury A, De Santis M, Kamat A, Stenzl A, Thoeny HC, Witjes JA. Current best practice for bladder cancer: a narrative review of diagnostics and treatments. Lancet. 2022 Nov 12;400(10364):1712-1721. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)01188-6. Epub 2022 Sep 26. PMID: 36174585","Lenis AT, Lec PM, Chamie K, Mshs MD. Bladder Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2020 Nov 17;324(19):1980-1991. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.17598. PMID: 33201207","Leslie SW, Soon-Sutton TL, Aeddula NR. Bladder Cancer. 2024 Aug 15. In: S